title: Grateful Dead Live at Cal State Dominguez Hills on 1990-05-06
description: Mississippi Half Step, Feel Like A Stranger, Easy To Love You, West L.A. Fadeaway, When I Paint My Masterpiece, Candyman, Victim Or The Crime, Foolish Heart Iko Iko, Samson & Delilah, The Weight, Blow Away, Terrapin Station-> Drums-> Jam-> The Other One-> Standing On the Moon-> Throwing Stones, Turn On Your Love Light, E: The Last Time

reviews.review_text: Almost as ... much of a Blow Away as the day before It's just  that the usual L.A. South Bay spring marine layer didn't blow in either day.
Great times INCREDIBLE SHOWS!!! Ones I will never forget!

download both Alaways liked Foolish as a first set closer and this one does not disappoint. Stabbed in the heart by Weir when he announces, "let's have a moment of silence for the celtics." 

Second set surprises made this show fantatstic. check both nights.

Terence & Tim Hey These two shows were some of my favorite from the Brent years. The one memory I have of these shows was seeing Terence McKenna & Tim Leary standing off to the side near the stage chatting & walking by them with my camera & forgetting to take a picture....

The song selection on these is excellent & I thought they played exceptionally well. It was hot & fun. KPFK was broadcasting it live & I think Healy was too. I like the sound on these. I have both audience & FM masters from these shows that sound about the same.

HOT ! ! ! These were my first West Coast shows and the only daytime GD shows I ever saw. I was about 15 feet back from the stage on Phil's side both days and I also saw Timothy Leary along with Bill Walton, hence the Celtics reference. I still have a picture somewhere of Leary wearing a pink suit up on the side of the stage. The other thing I remember about these shows (and 5/6 in particular) was the exteme heat. As I recall, it reached 103 degrees during the Sunday show.

These shows really do feature Brent at his high point. Also, I will never forget "One more crazy crazy afternoon" during Feel Like a Stranger.

Hot, so hot! I was there both days. One of the best of the last few Brent shows. The weather all week had been in the low 80s. Saturday and Sunday freaked out up to 102 & 104 degrees; in direct relation to the heat of the show, it seemed. So hot I scraped my scalp in the searing sun, blisters for days. 
The sound, from the taper section, chest pounding
crisp and clear.
The Other One: Brent feels late from Space break,
The boys drop kick a unified down beat, sort of 
final call for Brent....he scampered on stage and drove like a wild man.
Wierd tape scene that day. Some tapers brought in huge double speaker boom boxes to record
the fm broadcast. Unnecessary footage land grab...
Shows were the peak of the 1990 shows.

I remember! I saw a lot of the So Cal Dead shows between 1984 and 1992 or so....in fact, pretty much all of them!  And this one was memorable, I can remember Walton on crutches and us Laker fans good naturedly ribbing him a bit (OK, maybe more than a bit) as he hobbled out after this show.

At the time, being a purist, I was somewhat alarmed by all the new tunes, many of which I was hearing for the first time. But many came to grow on me, especially the epic Standing on the Moon that the master, Jerry G, ripped at this show.

Special props to Robespierre for sporting the custom tie dyes for this one, I still have that shirt somewhere!
Ahhh Yes Remeber this show well, One of the best I had experienced. Brent was awesome and the atmosphere was classic.....
